Scarce labelled faults make target-specific generator training and selection
compete with the same few examples needed for diagnosis. Trained generators
store physical knowledge in weights learned from data that few-shot regimes
cannot supply. We introduce \breeze, which externalizes class and machine
knowledge as an LLM-authored JSON recipe and converts it to a waveform through
a fixed seeded renderer without optimizing a target-data generator. A verifier
calibrated exclusively on the real outer-training split moves physical control
from a training objective to deterministic admission, bounded failure
feedback, and per-sample audit records. On file-disjoint PU, LLM recipes
outperform matched rule and random open-loop recipes for Accuracy and Macro-F1
at 5, 10, and 25 real windows per class; all \BreezePUPassedTests{} registered
comparisons pass Holm correction ($q<\BreezePUHolmBound$, 20 seeds), as do all
\BreezeCWRUPassedTests{} provenance-valid CWRU comparisons across within-load0
and held-out loads 1--3 (40 seeds). On case/run-disjoint Berkeley milling,
\BreezeBerkeleyPassedTests/\BreezeBerkeleyRegisteredTests{} comparisons pass,
including all \BreezeBerkeleyUnstructuredPassedTests{} against non-structured
baselines and the qualified lower-shot LLM--rule advantage;
class-conditional diagnostics and six failed PU cross-condition attempts locate
the supported operating range. A pass states train-calibrated admissibility,
and the combined evidence supports auditable LLM recipe generation with
physics-verified admission for the stated few-shot protocols.
